<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05102e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05102e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05102e"> 102(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> la personne / she</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In France, grammarians have disputed without end as to the propriety or not of referring to the (feminine) word <i>personnes</i> by means of the pronoun <i>ils</i> &hellip;: &ldquo;Les personnes que vous attendiez sont <i>tous log&eacute;s</i> ici.&rdquo; As a negative pronoun <i>personne</i> is now frankly masculine: &lsquo;personne n&apos;est <i>malheureux</i>.&rsquo; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJLN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJLN"><cite title="source">Language: its Nature, Development and Origin</cite></a> (Jan 1922) 346-347</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
